<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1425,2026]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493">
Pronotum divided into anterior and posterior lobes (
<figureCitation box="[795,865,1425,1450]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1970,1992]" captionText="FIGURE 2. Paravelia fanera male, pronotum, dorsal view. Scale 0.10 mm." pageId="2" pageNumber="493">
Fig. 
<number box="[849,865,1426,1450]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
); anterior lobe separated from posterior lobe by a transverse row of foveae, lacking a median carina. Pronotal and propleural surfaces covered with numerous foveae (
<figureCitation box="[159,226,1497,1522]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1404,1426]" captionTargetBox="[420,1152,672,1383]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[420,1166,661,1383]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Paravelia fanera male, head and anterior lobe of the pronotum, lateral view. Scale 0.10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219979/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="493">
Fig. 
<number box="[213,226,1498,1522]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Thoracic sternites lacking tubercles; posterior margins of prosternum, mesosternum, and margins of the first abdominal sternum bearing sinuous, shiny, black sulci (
<figureCitation box="[825,893,1533,1558]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="2.[151,250,728,750]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paravelia fanera female, pronotum, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm." pageId="2" pageNumber="493">
Fig. 
<number box="[877,893,1534,1558]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1425,2026]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493">
Abdomen with lateral margins rounded, wider on segment V. Connexiva slightly elevated at an angle of 
<number box="[1392,1421,1570,1594]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493" value="10.0">10</number>
º, posterolateral angles of tergite VIII lacking acute projections. Posterior margin of the abdominal sternite VII bearing prominent semi-triangular process (
<figureCitation box="[641,708,1641,1666]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1359,1381]" captionTargetBox="[550,1048,794,1330]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[526,1061,793,1345]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 4. Paravelia fanera male, apex of the abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219980/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="493">
Fig. 
<number box="[693,708,1642,1666]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
) projecting downward (
<figureCitation box="[978,1046,1641,1666]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="3.[151,250,671,693]" captionTargetBox="[515,1070,198,639]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[506,1081,193,650]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 5. Paravelia fanera male, apex of the abdomen, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219981/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="493">
Fig. 
<number box="[1030,1046,1641,1666]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Parameres symmetrical (
<figureCitation box="[1345,1413,1641,1666]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1115,1137]" captionText="FIGURE 6. Paravelia fanera male, paramere. Scale 0.010 mm." pageId="2" pageNumber="493">
Fig. 
<number box="[1397,1413,1641,1666]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1425,2026]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493">
Legs with all trochanters unarmed; fore tibia weakly expanded with grasping comb evident on apical onefourth (
<figureCitation box="[237,307,1713,1738]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1380,1402]" captionText="FIGURE 7. Paravelia fanera male, fore tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm." pageId="2" pageNumber="493">
Fig. 
<number box="[291,307,1714,1738]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
); fore femur with apical ¾ bearing a short spine (
<figureCitation box="[884,953,1713,1738]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1691,1713]" captionText="FIGURE 8. Paravelia fanera male, fore femur, lateral view. Scale 0.10 mm." pageId="2" pageNumber="493">
Fig. 
<number box="[938,953,1714,1738]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
); middle tibia with short, semi-recumbent pale setae on distal half of the posterior margin; hind femur slender, bearing a ventral row of four small spines (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1908,1930]" captionText="FIGURE 9. Paravelia fanera male, hind femur, lateral view. Scale 0.10 mm." pageId="2" pageNumber="493">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,167,1786,1810]" pageId="2" pageNumber="493" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
