<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,908,1149]" pageId="4" pageNumber="495">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,424,908,933]" pageId="4" pageNumber="495">Comparative notes</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[438,628,908,932]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="495" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fanera" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[438,628,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="495">Paravelia fanera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[635,697,908,933]" pageId="4" pageNumber="495" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[635,697,908,933]" pageId="4" pageNumber="495">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar in appearance and shape of the pronotum to 
<taxonomicName authority="Moreira, Nessimian &amp; Rudio, 2010" authorityName="Moreira, Nessimian &amp; Rudio" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="495" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capixaba">
<emphasis box="[1306,1320,909,932]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="495">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1333,1436,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="495">capixaba</emphasis>
Moreira, Nessimian &amp; Rúdio, 
<number box="[500,556,944,968]" pageId="4" pageNumber="495" value="2010.0">2010</number>
</taxonomicName>
but differs on the basis of several characters. Specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[1249,1352,944,968]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="495" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fanera">
<emphasis box="[1249,1263,945,968]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="495">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1279,1352,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="495">fanera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be diagnosed by the foveae on the pronotum and the propleurae (
<figureCitation box="[852,930,980,1005]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1404,1426]" captionTargetBox="[420,1152,672,1383]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[420,1166,661,1383]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Paravelia fanera male, head and anterior lobe of the pronotum, lateral view. Scale 0.10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219979/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="495">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[945,961,980,1004]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1970,1992]" captionText="FIGURE 2. Paravelia fanera male, pronotum, dorsal view. Scale 0.10 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="495">2</figureCitation>
), and posterior margins of the prosternum and mesosternum bearing sinuous, shiny, black sulci (
<figureCitation box="[749,817,1015,1040]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="2.[151,250,728,750]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paravelia fanera female, pronotum, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="495">
Fig. 
<number box="[801,817,1016,1040]" pageId="4" pageNumber="495" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). The male hind femur also bears four spines on ventral apical half (
<figureCitation box="[286,355,1052,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1908,1930]" captionText="FIGURE 9. Paravelia fanera male, hind femur, lateral view. Scale 0.10 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="495">
Fig. 
<number box="[339,355,1052,1076]" pageId="4" pageNumber="495" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
); abdominal sternite VII of male bears a semitriangular midle-ventral prolongation (
<figureCitation box="[1311,1392,1052,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1359,1381]" captionTargetBox="[550,1048,794,1330]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[526,1061,793,1345]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 4. Paravelia fanera male, apex of the abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219980/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="495">Figs. 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1405,1421,1052,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="3.[151,250,671,693]" captionTargetBox="[515,1070,198,639]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[506,1081,193,650]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 5. Paravelia fanera male, apex of the abdomen, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219981/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="495">5</figureCitation>
); and the male paramere is diagnostic (
<figureCitation box="[570,638,1087,1112]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1115,1137]" captionText="FIGURE 6. Paravelia fanera male, paramere. Scale 0.010 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="495">
Fig. 
<number box="[622,638,1087,1112]" pageId="4" pageNumber="495" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). In addition, the lateral and posterior margins of the abdominal tergite VIII in the female are covered with long setae (
<figureCitation box="[681,764,1124,1149]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="4.[151,250,841,863]" captionTargetBox="[459,1135,199,817]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[438,1148,193,820]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 10. Paravelia fanera female, apex of the abdomen, dorsal view. Scale 0.10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219982/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="495">
Fig. 
<number box="[733,764,1124,1148]" pageId="4" pageNumber="495" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
